Malaysia Stocks: Berjaya Food, Bina Puri, DRB, Perisai, Redtone

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-03-08T09:27:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/malaysia-stocks-berjaya-food-drb-perisai-petroleum-sunway.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  Malaysia  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 5 p.m. close in  Kuala
Lumpur .  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 1.92, or 0.1
percent, to 1,517.66.  Berjaya Food Bhd. (BFD MK), an operator of the Kenny Rogers
Roasters restaurant chain in Malaysia, jumped 25 percent to 63.5
sen on its listing debut. The company sold shares at 51 sen each,
according to its prospectus dated Feb. 18.        Bina Puri Holdings Bhd. (BIN)  , a builder, advanced 3.2
percent to 1.29 ringgit, the most since Feb. 2, after the
government said the company will develop a maritime and resort
project with two other companies.        DRB-Hicom Bhd. (DRB)  , an automotive assembler, climbed
4.9 percent to 1.94 ringgit, the largest gain since Feb. 8. The
company said it won a 7.55 billion-ringgit ($2.5 billion)
contract to supply the government with armored vehicles. The
contract to supply 257 vehicles is for a period of seven years,
DRB-Hicom said in a statement.        Perisai Petroleum Teknologi Bhd. (PPT)  , an oil and gas
services provider, advanced 3.5 percent to 60 sen, its highest
level since Feb. 21, after CIMB Investment Bank Bhd. rated the
stock new “outperform,” reflecting its earnings growth
prospects. The share estimate for the stock is 80 sen, Norziana
Mohd Inon, an analyst at CIMB, wrote in a report today.        Redtone International Bhd. (RIB)  , a telecommunications
services provider, jumped 22 percent to 22.5 sen, the biggest
increase since Nov. 5, 2009, after saying it will invest in a
national healthcare project in Malaysia with General Electric Co.        Sunway Holdings Bhd. (SGW)  , a construction and property
group, gained 2.7 percent to 2.26 ringgit, its steepest increase
since Jan 27. The company won a 74.1 million-ringgit building
contract from Malaysian Bio-XCell Sdn., according to a company
statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
